<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Remember</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->: Copyright violation is still copyright violation. You should always have permission before you use another work.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Step 1</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
In this case, I used Pat's <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.polykarbon.com/gallery/poly.html">Poly Profile</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> image. In hindsight, this was probably the wrong choice as there is some obvious compression artifacting, but that image clearly demonstrated what I wanted to show.<br>
Anyways... Save image to desktop.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Step 2</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Import image into Flash.<br>
Align it to the top left hand corner of the stage and then use Modify&gt;Movie &quot;Match Contents&quot; to make the stage size the same as the image. Notice I've actually scaled the image smaller.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://contest.polykarbon.com/tutorial/matchContents.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Step 3</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Use File&gt;Export Image.<br>
Choose jpg as the output file type.<br>
For portrait images, enter 8000 pixels into height (the max Flash will allow)<br>
For Landscape images, enter 8000 images into width.<br>
Use <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 1200 dpi</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for resolution and 100 for quality.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://contest.polykarbon.com/tutorial/example.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Export.<br>
Hope you have a fast computer...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Step 4</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Open jpg in Photoshop. Resize and resample as necessary. I've found the &quot;Dust and Scratches&quot; filter handy to minimize the effects of artifacting.<br>
<br>
<br>
Remember: You can't really improve on the quality of the original (not easily, that's for sure), but this is a GREAT way to get high resolution images from low res ones. <br>
